				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">bunnyboy wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If your sprite is at 0,0 and you move it left, it will now be at 255,0 and should display on the right side. If you move it up it will be at 0,255 which is off the viewing area at the bottom.</div><br />Any idea why the top and left clip while sprites can scroll smoothly off the right and bottom?<br /></div><br /><br />This is because wrap arounds don't occur. And also, the sprite is rendered left to right. Sprites are kept track of from the top left corner's X, Y coords. When the top left corner's X coordinate is $FF, it will be rendered first, and by the time the rest is supposed to be rendered, it's already too late. The rest of the sprite will not be rendered. The clipping is not present because of the fact that it keeps track of the sprites top left corner. If it were the top right corner, and they were rendered right to left, the clipping would be for the right side, and not the left.<br /><br />EDIT:<div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Celuis wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'd use sprite clipping, because the sudden disappearing is ugly. </div><br />I remeber you said me the other way arround one time. You said this was unnoticeable.</div>
<br />
<br />Well, I guess I changed my mind. It doesn't look good.</div>

					
